  "why": "The paper enforces semantic consistency by decomposing each input into a domain-invariant content vector and a domain-specific style vector (via MUNIT) and always recombining the learned style with the original content vectors when generating mutants. This means the semantically critical content (road layout, scene geometry) is held fixed while only environmental style is changed, matching the metamorphic-oracle assumption of semantic equivalence. Naturalness is enforced because styles are learned from real examples of the target environmental type (the MUNIT style space) and the authors validate realism via a user study that shows TACTIC-generated scenes are perceived as realistic and more realistic than affine/simulation baselines. Because mutations are performed by changing style vectors and recombining with the original content vectors (not by repeatedly mutating images), cumulative distortion/drift of semantic content across iterations is avoided. Together these satisfy both semantic consistency and naturalness requirements across fuzzing iterations.",
